captions:
Getting detailed images of the night sky is a challenge for amateur photographers, but Harvard undergraduate Christopher used resources from SEAS this summer to build his own astrophotography camera mount. 

Photographers know that lengthening a camera‚Äôs exposure allows in more light, but when photographing the night sky the Earth‚Äôs rotation becomes a challenge. While the sky might not seem to move to the naked eye, a camera pointed at a specific spot won‚Äôt actually be able to focus on it for a long exposure.

‚ÄúYou‚Äôll see what are called star streaks, where the dot moves across the image,‚Äù Christopher said.

Astrophotographers solve this problem with a camera mount that can automatically compensate for the earth‚Äôs spin, called an equatorial mount. Commercial mounts exist, but they often cost thousands of dollars, making them inaccessible to many amateur photographers.

Christopher applied for a Nectar fund, which supports student passion projects, to fabricate his own equatorial mount. With his mount, he was able to photograph a variety of stellar phenomena, including the Andromeda Galaxy, the Rosette Nebula, and the Pleiades star cluster. ‚ÄúMore or less every clear night, I‚Äôm outside setting up my equipment to take pictures of something new,‚Äù he said.

See our Story for even more details.

captions:
Nanotechnologists are using DNA and RNA as the raw material in efforts to build minuscule devices that could potentially function as drug-delivery vehicles. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Researchers at @wyssinstitute have used these features to design self-assembling nanostructures such as scaffolded DNA origami and DNA bricks of ever-growing sizes and complexities. However, the translation of these structures into medical and industrial applications is still challenging.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Now, researchers have developed entirely new types of origami that are folded from one single strand, which can be replicated in living cells, allowing their potential low-cost production at large scales and with high purities, opening entirely new opportunities for diverse applications such as drug delivery and nanofabrication.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#Harvard #dna #science

captions:
Researchers at Harvard are using drones to monitor unique chemical signals in the Amazon basin, home to the largest rainforest in the world.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
As the planet warms, drought, wildfire and changing weather patterns threaten some 400 billion trees in the Amazon, some of which are already at risk from logging and mining. As trees are damaged ‚Äî or killed ‚Äî they decompose and release carbon into the atmosphere. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
@harvardseas Professor Scot Martin, with an international team of researchers and collaborators from Amazonas State University and the Amazonas State Research Support Foundation, has developed an early detection system to monitor changes in the Amazon. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚ÄúWhat makes drone-based sensors so exciting is that they offer the possibility of collecting data at unexplored scales,‚Äù said Martin. ‚ÄúThis could lead to revolutionary insights into Amazonian ecosystems under climate stress and anticipated changes in climate and biodiversity.‚Äù‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#Harvard #climatechange

Harvard researchers have developed the first autonomous, untethered, and entirely soft robot. Built with 3D printers and pneumatically powered by controlled chemical reactions, these "octobots" could revolutionize how humans interact with machines.

The simplicity of the assembly process paves the way for designs of greater complexity. Next, the Harvard team hopes to design an octobot that can crawl, swim, and interact with its environment. ‚ÄúThis research is a proof of concept,‚Äù said Ryan Truby, a graduate student in the Lewis lab and co-first author of the paper. ‚ÄúWe hope that our approach for creating autonomous soft robots inspires roboticists, material scientists, and researchers focused on advanced manufacturing.‚Äù #Harvard #robot #robotics @wyssinstitute @harvardseas üêô

captions:
Engineers at Stanford have developed an open-source motion-capture app ‚Äì OpenCap ‚Äì that‚Äôs able to analyze human movement and forces in the musculoskeletal system using just a pair of smartphones ‚Äì at 1% of the cost.

Computational musculoskeletal analysis can help identify movement patterns that increase an athlete‚Äôs risk of injury or optimize treatments for individuals with mobility-limiting conditions. But such analysis has typically demanded significant time, equipment, expertise, and high costs.

‚ÄúOpenCap democratizes human movement analysis,‚Äù says Prof. Scott Delp. ‚ÄúWe hope it can put these once-out-of-reach tools in more hands than ever before.‚Äù

OpenCap computes how key body points, like knees, hips, and shoulders, move in three-dimensional space. It then uses complex models of the human musculoskeletal system to determine how the skeleton is moving and what forces are being applied during movement. From there, it can calculate important biomechanical data such as joint angles or joint loads, and provides a rich characterization of how humans move.

This September, students in a bronze and silver jewelry design course at the Stanford Product Realization Lab were treated to a special two-day visit by Navajo artists Zefren Anderson and Robert Blackhat Jr.

The artists reviewed designs, provided feedback, answered questions, and demonstrated techniques that combined cutting-edge technology with ones that have been honed over thousands of years.

‚ÄúThe creative cycle of thought, planning, creating, and revising jewelry fabrication follows the core philosophy of Navajo culture: only successful ideas proven over time are integrated into broader cultural practice,‚Äù Anderson said. ‚ÄúThe acceptance of failure in order to start a better plan builds better community knowledge.‚Äù

captions:
Meet TidyBot, the robot that learns to clean your space just the way you like it ü§ñ

The one-armed helper uses a large language model (a type of AI similar to the one used in ChatGPT) trained on massive amounts of information from the internet to identify broad categories of objects like clothes, food, and toys, and then put things away according to individualized instructions. 

Of course, with an 85% success rate, TidyBot does make occasional mistakes ‚Äì like when it spotted a visiting adviser during one of its demo runs. 

‚ÄúHe was visible in TidyBot‚Äôs ‚Äòplaying field,‚Äô‚Äù assistant professor Jeannette Bohg recalls, ‚Äúand TidyBot tried to pick him up.‚Äù

Luckily, it didn‚Äôt succeed: the team designed the robot mainly for handheld-sized objects or soft, deformable items like clothing. 

For now, TidyBot also struggles with difficult-to-grasp shapes, like a credit card lying flat on a table. But the researchers hope to improve robots‚Äô abilities to replicate human strategies in scenarios like this ‚Äì such as dragging the card to the table‚Äôs edge to pick it up. And they‚Äôd like to investigate whether multiple TidyBots could cooperate to accomplish bigger tasks like moving furniture or making a bed.

They‚Äôd also like it to generalize across environments as well as across objects. 

‚ÄúMaybe in the long term we can think about a more general-purpose robot that‚Äôs also able to cook my meal, make my bed, do my laundry,‚Äù assistant professor Shuran Song says. But for now, ‚ÄúIf I have a robot that‚Äôs able to reliably put my things away, that‚Äôs a pretty good goal to achieve.‚Äù

title: Stanford's Xi Beta Chapter of Alpha Kappa Alpha turns 40
captions:
June 25 marks four decades since the Xi Beta Chapter of Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority, Incorporated ‚Äì the oldest Greek-letter organization established by African American college-trained women ‚Äì was chartered at Stanford around traditions of sisterhood, scholarship and service.

During their time on campus, the women of Xi Beta have adopted a unique focus on supporting Black gender-marginalized people, and have worked to promote HBCUs, women‚Äôs health and wellness, economic well-being and the arts. Last summer, after the death of George Floyd, they rallied nearly 30 campus groups around Justice for Black Lives, a fundraiser that ultimately brought in more than $220,000 for the Marsha P. Johnson Institute, Black Mamas Matter Alliance, the Westside Justice Center and more.

‚ÄúAs a Stanford student, I feel I have the privilege and also the obligation to use the resources that are here and to help other people,‚Äù says Xi Beta president Celine Foster, ‚Äô21. ‚ÄúI hope folks can look at our chapter and see that with [the right] communities and people to support you, you can really do anything.‚Äù

title: George Shultz, 1920-2021
captions:
The Stanford scholar and former U.S. Secretary of State, who served three American presidents and played a pivotal role in shaping economic and foreign policy in the late 20th century, died Feb. 6 at his home on the Stanford campus. He was 100 years old.

One of the most consequential policymakers of all time and remembered as one of the most influential secretaries of state in American history, Shultz was a key player, alongside President Ronald Reagan, in changing the direction of history by using the tools of diplomacy to bring the Cold War to an end. He knew the value of one‚Äôs word, that ‚Äútrust was the coin of the realm,‚Äù and stuck unwaveringly to a set of principles. This, combined with a keen intelligence, enabled him not only to imagine things thought impossible but also to bring them to fruition and forever change the course of human events.

Shultz first joined Stanford in 1968 and had periodic affiliations with the university throughout his public service career, finally returning to campus in 1989. Always dedicated to his students and higher education, Shultz tackled some of humanity‚Äôs most difficult issues ‚Äì including nuclear disarmament, climate change and democratic governance ‚Äì in the classroom, in book and article form, and at events he hosted. Those issues drove him to keep working at Stanford nearly every day until his passing.

‚ÄúGeorge Shultz was a giant in public policy and world affairs, as well as a dedicated scholar and educator,‚Äù said Stanford President Marc Tessier-Lavigne. ‚ÄúHe was an extraordinary role model, a consummate bridge-builder in pursuit of the public good even beyond his hundredth birthday. His remarkable life and career serve as an inspiration to all those whose lives he touched at Stanford and beyond.‚Äù

title: Tracing the spread of COVID-19
captions:
Using anonymized cellphone data, Stanford researchers traced the movements of 98 million Americans in 10 major metropolitan areas to model the spread of #COVID19. 

Densely packed indoor establishments like restaurants, coffee shops and fitness centers were responsible for 8 in 10 coronavirus transmissions in the early stages of the pandemic, they found. 

The finding helps explain disproportionate rates of infection in low-income neighborhoods, where public venues tend to be more crowded and working from home is less of an option. 

Occupancy caps could be especially effective in reducing risk for vulnerable populations, sociologist David Grusky says. 

‚ÄúWe have a responsibility to build reopening plans that eliminate ‚Äì or at least reduce ‚Äì the disparities that current practices are creating.‚Äù 

More at¬†news.stanford.edu.

captions: Rice is the largest global staple crop, consumed by more than half the world‚Äôs population ‚Äì but new experiments from #Stanford suggest that with #climatechange, production in major rice-growing regions with endemic soil arsenic will undergo a dramatic decline and jeopardize critical food supplies. These experiments exploring rice production in future #climate conditions show rice yields could drop about 40 percent by 2100 ‚Äì with potentially devastating consequences in parts of the world that rely on the crop as a basic food source. What‚Äôs more, changes to soil processes due to increased temperatures will cause rice to contain twice as much toxic arsenic than the rice consumed today. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm optimistic that when people start shining a light on the threats that we see at a 5-degree Celsius impact, we won‚Äôt get there ‚Äî that people will wake up, [realize] that‚Äôs just unacceptable," Prof. Scott Fendorf says. "That‚Äôs my biggest hope.‚Äù Click on the link in our bio for more.

captions: Stanford chemists have developed a new deep-tissue #imaging technique that can see beneath the skin of living subjects to illuminate buried tumors with unparalleled clarity. (Here, the branching blood vessels of a brain inside a living mouse shift as the creature moves its head.) The technique, which relies on nanoparticles containing the rare-earth element erbium, could be used to predict the response of cancer patients to #immunotherapy and to track their progress following treatment. It could also enable surgeons to more precisely excise tumors and aid biologists and medical researchers in studying fundamental processes within cells. ‚ÄúIt is like seeing while driving on a highway before and after the fog evaporates on a winter day,‚Äù postdoctoral researcher Yeteng Zhong says. captions: Jay Hamilton, the Hearst Professor of Communication and director of #Stanford's #journalism program, spent the summer of 1980 opening mail at a congressman's office in #WashingtonDC, fielding constituent concerns about the economy, oil prices and television commercials. "I really wanted to solve puzzles that have a positive impact on society," he says, "and that's what I think academia, or at least social science, allows you to do." We asked Stanford faculty members to tell us about a summer job that ended up shaping life or career. To see more of their stories, visit news.stanford.edu.

captions: What makes birds so good at sticking their landings, even in the most unlikely of places? Stanford engineers have been looking for answers with a team of parrotlets, five high-speed cameras and an arsenal of sensor-packed perches. The information they‚Äôve gathered could some day inform the design of flying robots with similar abilities. (Emphasis on some day.) ‚ÄúWhen we look at a person running, a squirrel jumping or a bird flying,‚Äù graduate student William Roderick says, ‚Äúit‚Äôs clear that we have a long way to go before our technology can reach the complex potential of these animals, both in terms of efficiency and controlled athleticism.‚Äù Click on the link in our bio for more. üìπ: @kurthickman

captions: A new intensive takes #Stanford undergraduates through the entirety of the #humanities research process over the course of only five days, and it starts in a sort of archival "petting zoo": a Green Library room full of books and objects that span 800 years of history. Students are given a couple of hours to look at the materials‚Äîwhich include artifacts like a 13th-century French Bible written on animal skin, a 17th-century book about the coronation of King James II, and 19th-century immigration pamphlet‚Äîand pick an object that interests them. They then have to come up with a research question about the object and write a five-page proposal for a research project by the end of the week. ‚ÄúPeople often think that humanities research is [about] getting some books of poetry and reading them, but that‚Äôs only one kind of humanities research,‚Äù English Professor Elaine Treharne says. ‚ÄúThere is actually a tremendous amount of excitement to be generated about the relics of the past which human endeavor has produced. Archival #research is about being able to contextualize, read and describe objects and put them into a broader social and cultural set of significances, often by using digital tools and approaches, too.‚Äù Click on the link in our bio for more.
name: Stanford University

captions: Manu Prakash is known for low-cost, curiosity driven science. His latest discovery started with open-ended observation of life in a marsh near the Stanford campus. He was peering through a $1.75 paper microscope of his own invention when something swam by and caught his eye. It was single-cell organism that turned out to have a special power. Without touching and without electrical or chemical signals, it can coordinate ultrafast contractions with its neighbors. Groups of the organism appear to shrink simultaneously ‚Äì a reaction to predators that makes them release paralyzing toxins in sync. How do they do it? Back in the lab, Prakash and his colleagues spent years exploring a new type of hydrodynamic communication between cells. Their findings are detailed in a new paper. (Link in bio.) "What's surprising about working out in nature is the fact that we really don't know what life is capable of," Prakash says. "The next time you find a puddle of water, take the time, collect some samples. Who knows what you'll discover?" Watch the complete story on IGTV. üìπ: @kurthickman

captions:
‚ÄúI had a three-year identity crisis in college. I started out majoring in molecular biology, but during my second semester of college I randomly took an introductory course in world religion and fell in love with it. Unfortunately, I was at one of the few institutions that allowed you to choose only one major ‚Äì no dual majors, no minors, no certificates, no study abroad. My loophole ended up being that there was no limit on the number of classes I could take. For the rest of college, I took classes toward my degree while also taking tons of courses in world religion, history, and languages. I wasn‚Äôt yet ready to let go of molecular biology, but I was increasingly passionate about history. Both fields offer a sense of discovery. After graduating, I decided to pursue graduate work in ancient religions and became a professor of religious studies. At Stanford, I have the exciting opportunity to be part of large, collaborative research. I work with computer scientists, data scientists, and software developers, within and outside of our university. Some of my current research involves using advances in how computers analyze modern handwriting for security software to help match up handwriting from ancient scribes. This helps us figure out when manuscripts were written, by whom, and the connections between them. And I get to be one of the first to uncover these findings! I look at artifacts like ancient cow hides that haven‚Äôt been seen for over a millennium ‚Äì precious pieces in a larger historical puzzle. It‚Äôs exciting to discover new parts of history and share that context with the world, bringing light to our past as well as our present.‚Äù - Michael Penn, professor of religious studies 
Click on the link in our bio for more from #MeetOurFaculty. üì∏: @hollyhernandezphoto

captions:
Lost in the little stuff? Step into #JosiahMcElheny's monumental installation at @cantorarts, which attempts to visualize nothing less than the Big Bang. Working at the intersection of #physics, the history of #Modernism and #art, McElheny imagines a multiverse scenario, where five separate universes ‚Äî suspended sculptures inspired by the chandeliers at the @metopera house ‚Äî occupy the same space, frozen in their individual moments of expansion. Each is a rigorous reflection of ideas developed by the worldwide scientific community, and McElheny collaborated closely with astronomy professor David Weinberg of @theohiostateuniversity to make the calculations and conceptualize the forms. Another 100 or so people, many from the aerospace industry (and some who made parts for the Mars landers), contributed to the construction of chromed aluminum, electric lighting and blown-glass components. "Island Universe" is on view at #Stanford through August 18. Click on the link in our bio for more.

captions: Does a galloping horse ever lift all four feet off the ground at once? Leland Stanford hired San Francisco photographer Eadweard Muybridge to prove the answer was yes. With a series of 24 cameras spaced 12 inches apart, electrically tripped in rapid succession; split-second shutter speeds; and the help of a Central Pacific mechanical engineer, Muybridge published the first series of photographs of horses in motion in the summer of 1878. The next year, he projected these "motion pictures" in San Francisco. üì∑: Eadweard Muybridge, (England, 1830 - 1904, England), ‚ÄúSallie Gardner‚Äù Running at a 1:40 Gait, 1878. Albumen print. captions:
A bio-printer in development at Stanford could speed diagnosis of bacterial blood infections and reduce the use of ineffective antibiotics. It relies on acoustic pulses that shoot through a blood sample from an ailing patient, pushing individual droplets onto a piece of paper. The print-out can be scanned with a laser and the colors of light that bounce off the page reveal each cell type present within the droplets. Machine-learning algorithms analyzing the light can detect the presence of bacteria, all in a matter of minutes.

Video credit: Fareeha Safir

captions:
Suited up in protective gear similar to that worn by Ebola workers, students of biology professor Craig Heller helped test solutions to overheating in hazmat suits. The recent Ebola outbreak in Congo highlights why this matters: When health care workers overheat, they're in danger of not only illnesses such as heat stroke, but also compromised mental and physical capabilities.
.
Heller has developed a new cooling system made of a hydration backpack that contains a frozen water bladder set against a bladder of fluid that circulates. Tubes that come from the backpack constantly feed that cooling fluid into and out of pads placed into the underside of fingerless gloves, taking away heat from networks of veins in the wearer's palms. To regulate the glove's temperature, a valve combines the warm returning fluid with chilled fluid coming from the heat exchanger. The next step is getting it to professionals who deal with overheating, such as firefighters and health care workers wearing personal protective equipment. Read more: stanford.io/2tbAvkH üé•: @kurthickman

captions:
The physics of stirring your coffee are more like the principles of bitcoin transactions than you‚Äôd think. Applied physics doctoral student William Gilpin used his free time on winter break to discover that the equations of mixing a fluid fit the requirements for the hash functions that secure our digital information almost perfectly. Mathematically, hash functions make it easy for computers to track cryptocurrencies but hard for hackers to do the same: ‚ÄúIt suggests that there‚Äôs something more fundamental going on with how chaotic math is acting,‚Äù said Gilpin.
Video courtesy of William Gilpin

captions:
Swimming on its own, a tiny sea monkey wisps through water, causing only a ripple. But a swarm of millions or billions of zooplankton can have an outsized effect on their environment, @StanfordEng's John Dabiri and colleagues have found. By day the small organisms live hundreds of meters below the ocean surface, but as they rise at night to feed, they create a downward flow of water likely strong enough to stir their surroundings and alter the ocean's nutrient distribution, possibly even influencing climate models.
.
Zooplankton swim in response to light, so Dabiri used lasers to control their migration and study their fluid mechanics. The flows were powerful enough to mix the tank‚Äôs salt gradient irreversibly. Dabiri says the findings might reflect an important coupling between organisms and the ocean. "The work suggests that the effects of our pollution, of over-fishing, of the acidification of the ocean, might have more severe consequences than we currently appreciate," he says.
.
üé•: @kurthickman
üéµ: Morningview by deeB/ Chillhop Records
name: Stanford University

captions:
‚ÄúI call what I do conjure art. My work is rooted in social justice and ritual, and so basically I utilize spiritual ritual in non-traditional ways to think about ways that we can change the vibration of an issue, as opposed to just educate people on an issue through performance.
.
‚ÄúI‚Äôm a contemporary choreographer but my movement draws from different dance forms from the African Diaspora. In classes I teach, we‚Äôve focused on Afro-Cuban and Afro-Brazilian dances that have informed contemporary dance, and that evoke the orisha divinities that come from the Yoruba tradition in Nigeria. Orisha are based in the belief that every aspect of nature is representative of a certain divinity. Each orisha has an in-balance and an out-of-balance state and is connected to nature - not only our physical nature and environment, but our human nature.
.
‚ÄúAt Stanford, I direct the Committee on Black Performing Arts (CBPA) and am an artist-in-residence in @StanfordTAPS. CBPA was formed in 1968 by students demanding racial justice in response to the assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.
.
‚ÄúToday at CBPA, we really want to create room for experimentation and encourage artists to explore outside of definition and forms, and to be in a process where they can show work that‚Äôs in progress. We also want students to be mentored by artists ‚Äì including alumni artists ‚Äì and to have residencies and performances and actually engage. Rolling around what looks like Mister Rogers' Neighborhood, these student-built robots have one mission: find animals in need of rescue. To do this, they must first map their surroundings ‚Äî roads, trees, etc. ‚Äî and also tell the difference between, say, an angry bear and a lost kitten.
.
As part of a robotic autonomy class, students build the different components of the autonomy software and then integrate and deploy them into their robots.
.
A functioning whole autonomous vehicle is much harder to achieve than the sum of its components, says Benoit Landry, a graduate student in aeronautics and astronautics and teaching assistant for the class. ‚ÄúSo that‚Äôs really something that we‚Äôre trying to emphasize: How do you piece all of these complicated parts together to make a whole that works?‚Äù he says.

captions:
"This piece is alive and it's still being molded in the process of us working on it," said violist Jennie Yang, '19, of rehearsing with Danny Elfman for performances of his first violin concerto. Elfman is best known for his work in film, particularly for collaborating with director Tim Burton on movies including The Nightmare Before Christmas and Batman. "Not only is he a well-known composer, but he's trying something new and we're part of that experience," Yang said. Recently, Stanford Symphony Orchestra members were the first musicians in the United States to perform Elfman's Concerto for Violin and Orchestra: Eleven Eleven. The composer took careful notes and provided feedback during the final days of rehearsal at Bing Concert Hall.
.
"This is still a work in progress," said Elfman, whose violin concerto premiered in Prague in 2017. "There's a couple of new sections here that I've never heard before. There's new bits of orchestration. So I'm trying to listen. This is the hardest thing I've ever worked on," Elfman said. ‚ÄúI really saw that the students had arrived prepared, and so I‚Äôm very happy with the results.‚Äù

captions:
Rachael Flatt was just 17 years old when she represented the United States at the 2010 Winter Olympics. She put on the performance of her life but didn‚Äôt receive full credit for two of her highest-scoring jump passes, and placed 7th. Flatt had skated professionally for so long that she had trouble relinquishing that identity after she retired in 2014, even as she was filling that gap with a pre-med course load at Stanford. Her senior year she worked in a lab that focused on body-image studies, and she realized that her experiences with body shaming as a skater ‚Äì crowds called her ‚ÄúRachael Fat‚Äù ‚Äì provided her a unique insight into the psychology of athletes. Now, she plans to pursue a doctorate in psychology so she can build and share the tools she needed as an athlete at the top of her game and in transition to a new life. More from @StanfordAlumni: http://stanford.io/2Gf3BUe

captions: The black and white image is a typical chest X-ray that physicians might look at to diagnose pneumonia. The Dorothy-in-the-land-of-Oz version of the same patient shows how a new #Stanford2017 algorithm developed by machine learning researchers can provide a more accurate diagnosis. By training their tool on images of diseased lungs, the research team developed an algorithm that can better identify the signs of disease, which are tricky to spot with the naked eye. Here, the red areas are those that the algorithm interprets as most likely to represent pneumonia. This tool can diagnose pneumonia better than expert radiologists working alone, and in doing so could help reduce the amount of missed cases of pneumonia and lead to faster diagnoses for the sickest patients. The researchers can use this tool to diagnose up to 14 types of medical conditions. For more head here: http://stanford.io/2isKQDx

Stroll through Memorial Court to spend a moment with Auguste Rodin‚Äôs Burghers of Calais (modeled 1884-1895). The bronze figures installed near the entrance to the Main Quad depict an episode from the Hundred Years‚Äô War during the 14th century when six prominent leaders of the French port Calais surrendered to stop England‚Äôs siege on their town.
.
@cantorarts holds more than 200 Rodin works and archival materials in its collection, the majority of which entered between 1974-1992 and were gifts from Iris and B. Gerald Cantor and the Cantor Foundation. B. Gerald Cantor (1916-1996) was a financier and philanthropist whose deep love for Rodin's art led him to amass a collection of hundreds of sculptures. During the course of his collecting, Mr. Cantor established a close working relationship with the late Stanford professor and Rodin scholar Albert Elsen (1927-1995), and it is because of this connection that a portion of the Cantor collection can be seen at Stanford today. @stanfordarts
.

Students surrender their smartphones at the beginning of a two-week @stanfordearth Sophomore College course in Southern Alaska, and immerse themselves in the study of geology, climate, and the region's social-ecological systems. "I never really knew where my food was coming from, where my power was coming from, or anything like that. I was really disconnected from the land that I was using," said Mateusz "Matt" Wojtaszek, '18, a chemical engineering major. "But here, people know what they're taking from the environment and what they're putting back in. It's a very different way of thinking, and I think I'll try to carry that on past this Sophomore College." The students get classroom time but do most of their learning in the fied. ‚ÄúI was wet, and cold, and literally soaked from my shoulders down, but it was sheer magic to be able to see whales, and sea otters, and sea lions all around me,‚Äù said Chris Yeh, ‚Äô18, after an impromptu beach hike and kayak trip to study local wildlife. #EarthDay

captions:
Convincing a bird to fly through a laser field provides a precise method of testing theoretical models of how birds generate enough lift to fly. Researchers in David Lentink‚Äôs lab wanted to keep their beloved parrotlets safe during the experiment, so they designed special laser-proof goggles for the birds (that‚Äôs Obi in the video). Once all humans and birds were fully goggled, Lentink‚Äôs team was able to create a clear visualization of the vortices created by each wingbeat, and to calculate the force generated in each stroke. In addition to upending long-held predictions of how the vortices propagate, these insights into how animals fly can inspire nature-tested designs for robotic flight.

When Robert Moses was a young dancer with @ABTofficial, @odcsf and @twylatharp, he threw himself into performance with the spirit of an athlete. Today, his artistic life is less about performance, the ‚Äújumping over people‚Äôs heads,‚Äù and more about sharing‚Äîwith himself, with students, with other dancers.
 
In addition to teaching at Stanford, Moses choreographs, recently for @alvinailey and @dance_stl, and leads the San Francisco-based company @RobertMosesKin. He also writes, makes films and composes music. (The track heard here is his own.)
 
That backstage work isn‚Äôt only about preparation for something public. It‚Äôs about letting dance escape the ego, letting movement alone justify its own existence.
 
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs satisfying to just be in there doing it,‚Äù Moses says, ‚Äúthe amazing, beautiful, wonderful things that nobody else will ever see.‚Äù

captions: The basement room where Mia Allende works looks like any standard materials lab ‚Äî a scattering of scales, tins, sieves and industrial kitchen equipment. But closer inspection of container labels tells a different story: The mission here is anything but earthbound. Allende, a doctoral candidate in civil and environmental engineering, and her colleagues are designing a concrete substitute that early settlers of the moon and Mars could manufacture in situ, eliminating the need for expensive shipments from Earth. Their current candidate, a biocomposite made of planetary soil and locally farmed protein ‚Äúglue,‚Äù could be 3-D printed as landing and launching pads, roads, habitats and more - but design challenges are significant. Structures on Mars will need to withstand harsh radiation and abrasive dust. And surface systems on the moon will be subjected to frequent pelting by micrometeorites, traveling at speeds averaging 45,000 mph. For slow-motion footage of the biocomposite bricks undergoing hypervelocity impact experiments at #NASA's Ames Vertical Gun Range, click on the link in our bio.

captions:
It‚Äôs an object that is small but mighty ‚Äî and a remnant from a time when archrivals didn‚Äôt just get mad at each other. They got even.

Known as a ‚Äúcurse tablet,‚Äù which was acquired five years ago by the @beineckelibrary, this thin sheet of lead is about the size of a playing card. On it are inscribed 10 lines of ancient Doric Greek script that curses four different men who were involved in a lawsuit in the courts of ancient Sicily around 450 BCE.

These days, Jessica Lamont, a social and cultural historian at Yale, uses the tablet in her classical antiquity classes, including seminars on Greek and Roman magic, epigraphy, Greek history, and the ancient Greek language.

There‚Äôs no telling who came out on top in the legal case memorialized on the tablet ‚Äî the curser or the cursed ‚Äî but belief in the efficacy of curses was strong enough that these tablets were offered up to the gods of the underworld by ancient Greeks and Romans for some 1,000 years, says Lamont.

üîó Tap the link in our bio to read more. #Yale

It seems like they should be. They‚Äôre made of paper, after all. But those cups contain a thin plastic coating on the inside that makes them non-recyclable. Remembering ‚ÄòAmnesia‚Äô: A new exhibit at Yale‚Äôs Sterling Memorial Library examines ‚ÄúAmnesia,‚Äù a groundbreaking video game released in 1986, and the library‚Äôs efforts to preserve it.

In the text-only video game, players inhabit the perspective of a man experiencing memory loss while staying in midtown Manhattan at the fictional Sunderland Hotel. Players must negotiate a series of puzzles to find much-needed clothes, leave the hotel, and navigate Manhattan‚Äôs busy streets. By gathering clues and avoiding innumerable pitfalls, they gradually discover that the protagonist has a fianc√©e he cannot remember, is being pursued by an assassin, and is wanted for murder in Texas.

A groundbreaking digital work of interactive fiction by the sci-fi novelist Thomas M. Disch, the game anchors ‚ÄúRemembering Amnesia: Rebooting the first computerized novel,‚Äù an exhibit on view through March 2 in the Hanke Exhibition Gallery.

üîó Tap the link in our bio to learn more about @yalelibrary‚Äôs new exhibit. #Yale

In parts of Bangladesh, rising sea levels are creating a water crisis for millions of people and groundwater salinity threatens rice crop cultivation and agriculture jobs. 

‚ÄúWhen water gets too salty, rice is not as productive. But it‚Äôs also leading to some human problems like a lack of access to drinking water,‚Äù said Mushfiq Mobarak, professor of economics and management at Yale.

‚ÄúWe need to rise to that challenge,‚Äù said Mobarak, who explores ways to inspire people in developing countries to adopt technologies or behaviors that could help.

Mobarak participated in a panel discussion at Yale @ Climate Week NYC on Thursday. The summit coincides with #ClimateWeekNYC, the largest annual climate event of its kind, and a meeting of the UN General Assembly.

Take a deep dive into Yale‚Äôs new Tech Tank!

The technology behind amphibious robotics, marine observation devices, and other water-based innovations has progressed dramatically in recent years. Finding research facilities that can keep up with these advances, though, has proved tricky.

To that end, Yale University recently introduced its own Tech Tank, a specialized facility for testing such advanced technologies under very specific and tightly controlled conditions.

Housed in a former warehouse at @yalewestcampus, the 20,000-gallon tank features a wave generator, a moveable mesh ramp, and climate control. It‚Äôs 40 feet long, 10 feet wide, and the water is six feet deep.

Although the tank is managed by the Yale School of Engineering & Applied Science, it will be open to researchers in all fields, both at Yale and beyond. The tank is the latest development in @yaleengineering‚Äôs commitment to robotics, an initiative that has doubled the number of faculty focusing on robotics at the school.

üîó Tap the link in our profile to dive deeper into the Tech Tank. #Yale

The public is often closed off from scholarly perspectives on the potential benefits of generative artificial intelligence (AI). Studies often reside behind pricey paywalls. And even if they are accessible, they are frequently written in esoteric language that non-academics struggle to parse.

Nicolas Gertler, a first-year student in Yale College, saw a potential solution to these obstacles, through generative AI‚Äôs own capabilities.

Gertler, a research assistant at Yale‚Äôs Digital Ethics Center (DEC), has spearheaded an experiment using generative AI to make bodies of knowledge broadly accessible. With Rithvik ‚ÄúRicky‚Äù Sabnekar, a high school junior and skilled developer from Texas, he created the Luciano Floridi Bot, also known as LuFlot, a free AI-powered online educational tool designed to foster engagement with the works of Yale philosopher and DEC Director Luciano Floridi, a pioneer in the philosophy of information and one of the most-cited living philosophers.

The developers believe it‚Äôs the first time a chatbot has been trained on an academic‚Äôs corpus of literature and released to the public for free.

üîó Tap the link in our profile for more on how LuFlot Bot is answering questions on the ethics of digital technology. #Yale @yaledec

Darwin Armenta, a senior at the Cooperative Arts and Humanities High School in New Haven, spends most Tuesday evenings rehearsing with a mariachi band. He grew up listening to the music, a distinct Mexican folk genre that combines brass and strings, at home. And, at 17, he has played violin and sung vocals in several community mariachi groups for the past decade.

‚ÄúThat‚Äôs where I got my shyness out,‚Äù he said.

But the band he plays with now rehearses at historic Hendrie Hall, on the Yale campus. The group is a new addition to the All-City Ensembles, an after-school program that is part of the Yale School of Music‚Äôs Music in Schools Initiative (MISI), a partnership with New Haven Public Schools made possible by a gift from the Yale College Class of 1957.

Through the program, local students get the benefit of free instruction from accomplished graduate students, while the public school teachers who help lead the ensembles receive tutelage in conducting skills.

Since it was launched in 2010, All-City has offered a choir, a band for brass, woodwinds, and percussion, and a strings ensemble, most of which rehearse in spaces on the Yale campus.

captions:
Excited for the eclipse?! #Yale #SolarEclipse
 
The solar eclipse on Monday, April 8, 2024 ‚Äî when the sun, moon, and earth are in a direct line ‚Äî will mark the last *total* solar eclipse visible from parts of the contiguous U.S. until August 2044.
 
‚ÄúA solar eclipse is a phenomenon that‚Äôs really special to the Earth,‚Äù said Meg Urry, Israel Munson Professor of Physics and Astronomy in Yale‚Äôs Faculty of Arts and Sciences and director of the Yale Center for Astronomy & Astrophysics.
 
‚ÄúIt looks as if the moon is moving in front of the sun,‚Äù Urry said. ‚ÄúAnd then, at the last part, it gets really dark. It gets like nighttime.‚Äù
 
Only when the moon completely blocks the visible surface of the sun during a total solar eclipse can viewers watch without special solar filter glasses, said Urry. Looking at the sun without proper eye protection outside the narrow path of totality is unsafe.
 
Eye protection will be needed for the duration of the eclipse in Connecticut, which is not within the path of totality. It is still fairly close, however, allowing for a partial eclipse event starting at about 2:13 p.m. in the New Haven area, according to Yale‚Äôs Leitner Family Observatory and Planetarium.
 
‚ÄúFor people who are seeing an eclipse for the first time, I hope they get the sense of wonder,‚Äù Urry said.
 
üîó Tap the link in our bio for more from @nasa on when, where, and how to safely view the upcoming solar #eclipse. Get your glasses ready! üï∂Ô∏è ‚òÄÔ∏è @lfop.yale @yaleastronomy

Science in motion: Predicting a dinosaur‚Äôs stride ü¶ñ 

Researchers have developed a new way to visualize how ancient animals moved as they roamed the Earth ‚Äî starting with a Yale-discovered dinosaur‚Äôs sickle-clawed foot.

The new approach, which uses computer animation software to combine 3D models of fossil bones with information gleaned from X-ray videos of the moving joints of modern animal species, could change our understanding of how prehistoric creatures chased prey, swam coastal waterways, soared across the sky, climbed over difficult terrain, and ate breakfast.

captions:
Creating art as a climate solution. #Yale #NewHaven

Urban settings are disproportionately affected by the consequences of climate change, but Yale School of the Environment‚Äôs Karen Seto believes that the world‚Äôs cities can also be a key part of the climate solution.

A New Haven-based collaboration developed by Seto and Kymberly Pinder, Dean of the Yale School of Art, is a case in point.

After hearing about a new kind of paint that more effectively absorbs heat (and thus reduces surface temperatures), it occurred to Seto that the advance might offer a chance to mitigate the effects of climate change. What‚Äôs more, she saw it as opportunity for scholars from across disciplines to educate the local community and inspire action.

Pinder, a renowned scholar of public art and advocate for promoting community engagement in the arts, agreed. The first project to emerge from their partnership is a vibrant mural, called ‚ÄúTake the Risk to Cool Down,‚Äù in Fair Haven, a neighborhood of New Haven. 

The mural, which was painted on a building at the corner of Mill Street and Saltonstall Avenue, was created by Victoria Martinez ‚Äô20 M.F.A., Yale‚Äôs Climate Engagement through Art in Cities fellow.

üîó Tap the link in our profile to learn more about how this piece of public art is just a first step in a greater initiative. @environmentyale @yaleschoolofart @victoria_martinez_studio

Chiara Mingarelli, a physicist with a passion for science communication, devotes much of her professional time to deciphering the furtive chirps of gravitational waves from the far reaches of the universe.

But that is not her only entry point for the ways that science speaks to us across vast distances. She recently arranged a conversation between graduate students in her Yale astrophysics lab, undergraduate students in her General Physics Lab, and some of history‚Äôs greatest mathematicians, physicists, chemists, and astronomers.

Mingarelli and her crew descended to a lower-level room at the Beinecke Rare Book & Manuscript Library, part of Yale University Library, where they commiserated with Johannes Kepler over the drudgery of long division and reveled in Sir Isaac Newton‚Äôs relationship with the universe.

Galileo, Da Vinci, Du Ch√¢telet, Faraday, Copernicus ‚Äî all were represented here, speaking their truth via the groundbreaking science texts that changed humanity‚Äôs perception of the world. More than a dozen of their works rested on plump brown pillows in the center of the room, waiting to be perused.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs rare to see a collection of important scientific books like this, all in one place,‚Äù said Mingarelli, an assistant professor of physics in Yale‚Äôs Faculty of Arts and Sciences and curator of this ‚Äúpop-up‚Äù exhibit. ‚ÄúI think it‚Äôs important for students to understand these scientists were real people with foibles and problems.‚Äù

üîó Tap the link in our bio to read more in Yale News. #Yale

How can we engineer immune cells to detect and treat disease earlier? We‚Äôre launching a new research hub in New York to harness the full potential of immune cells to better detect and treat diseases before they progress.

#CZBiohubNY will study immune cells and decode their warning language using single-cell biology tools and AI. With a better understanding of these immune cells, Biohub scientists and engineers will program them to navigate to specific organs and tissues to examine their health and deliver treatments to stop diseases from progressing. This could enable us to detect and eliminate tumors in their earliest stages or repair organ function after damage.

The immune system is incredibly complex, but with the expertise of scientists and engineers at @columbia, @rockefelleruniv and @yale, we‚Äôre excited to see this work one day transform how we track human health and disease‚Äîincluding diseases that are hard to detect at an early stage like ovarian and pancreatic cancers and neurodegenerative diseases.

#science #engineering #collaboration #healthresearch #inflammation #nyc

Fun facts about this First Folio:

‚ñ™Ô∏è The Folio, published in 1623, preserved 18 of Shakespeare‚Äôs plays that had never been printed before.
‚ñ™Ô∏è It was the first book to divide Shakespeare‚Äôs plays by genre: comedies, histories and tragedies.
‚ñ™Ô∏è The Folio‚Äôs engraved portrait of Shakespeare is thought to be one of the most authentic likenesses of the playwright.
‚ñ™Ô∏è Copies of the First Folio are not rare ‚Äî more than 200 are known to exist.
‚ñ™Ô∏è The Folio now on display in the Hanke Exhibition Gallery belongs to the Elizabethan Club of Yale University.

Curious about K-pop?

Initially a musical subculture popular in South Korea during the 1990s, Korean Pop, or K-pop, has transformed into a global cultural phenomenon.

Characterized by catchy hooks, polished choreography, grandiose live performances, and impeccably produced music videos, K-pop ‚Äî including music by groups like BTS and BLACKPINK ‚Äî now frequently tops the Billboard charts, attracts a fiercely dedicated online following, and generates billions of dollars.

Yale sociologist Grace Kao, who became fascinated with the music after watching a 2019 performance by BTS on Saturday Night Live, now studies the subgenres of K-pop and its cultural, sociological, and political effects.

Learn more and listen to Kao‚Äôs ‚ÄúIntro to K-pop‚Äù playlist via the link in our bio. #Yale #kpop

Lessons from the land: Cultivating community at the Yale Farm üöú 

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs been like the best crash course in everything that I‚Äôve wondered about food,‚Äù said Rebecca Salazar ‚Äô26, one of six Yale College students taking part in the Lazarus Summer Internship program on a one-acre parcel of land known as the Yale Farm.

Offered by the Yale Sustainable Food Program since 2003, the 10-week internship teaches principles of sustainable agriculture and the critical thinking skills required to manage complex agricultural systems. 

The students incorporate the tenets they learn on the farm in their chosen course of study, said Jeremy Oldfield, manager of field academics at the Yale Farm.

‚ÄúWe use the problems, challenges, and opportunities of agriculture to create an inhabitable external classroom for all sorts of teaching disciplines at Yale and community members around here,‚Äù Oldfield said.

captions:
12,641 pipes, 142 stops, 30,000 pneumatic valves ‚Äì one incredible sound.
 
Perhaps there is no one better suited to demonstrate the power and versatility of Yale‚Äôs historic Newberry Memorial Organ than Thomas Murray, Professor Emeritus of Organ at the Yale Institute of Sacred Music. For 38 years, Murray taught graduate organ performance majors on this world-renowned instrument at Woolsey Hall.
 
The Newberry Organ was built in 1903, renovated in 1915, and rebuilt and expanded in 1928. While other similar pipe organs from that era fell into disrepair or were replaced, Yale‚Äôs remains in original condition, thanks to a dedicated team of expert curators.
 
‚ÄúWe are hearing the same sounds that the crowd heard when this was dedicated for the third time,‚Äù said Murray, who joined the School of Music and Institute of Sacred Music faculty in 1981 and became university organist in 1990. Though he retired in 2019, Murray‚Äôs connection to the university ‚Äì and to its magnificent organ ‚Äì endures to this day.
 
‚ÄúThe world needs to know how special it is, and Yale is very fortunate to have it,‚Äù he said.
 
Learn more about the history, restoration, and maintenance of the Newberry Organ by clicking the link in our profile. #Yale @yaleism @yale.music

Several of these actions are in collaboration with the Connecticut Governor‚Äôs Office, which made a parallel announcement on ‚Äúa series of new steps that respond to Secretary Yellen‚Äôs call for states to implement inclusive and green policies and for academic economists to deploy their skills in support of state efforts.‚Äù
 
President Peter Salovey also announced the Tobin Center is launching a major new program on climate economics in support of Yale‚Äôs Planetary Solutions Project, a signature university-wide initiative.

From inspiration to art.

A few weeks ago, we introduced you to Sarah Tang, an art history major who paints her favorite views of Yale and New Haven. Now, we are seeing some of the images she used as a guide to create her stunning artwork.

In 2019, when Tang was a first-year student at Yale, she often snapped cell phone photographs of the beauty of campus and the Elm City. Using her snapshots as inspiration, Tang later painted those campus scenes, landscapes, and architecture.

In this short video, you‚Äôll see how she transformed those initial photos into paintings that she ‚Äì and now many others ‚Äì enjoy.

Working in acrylic paint, usually in a small format, Tang has captured the building housing retail shops at the corner of York Street near Broadway; the view down Wall Street from College Street; and several homes that caught her eye in the East Rock neighborhood.

captions:
#WednesdayWisdom: @YaleSOM faculty members put a scholarly lens on improving our personal and professional lives in the coming year. Other highlights:

üì∏ ‚ÄúAs photo-taking has become ubiquitous, so is the belief that photo-taking detracts from an experience. It‚Äôs a belief that I held for years, too ‚Äî until I did the research. This kind of documentation not only boosts enjoyment, but further improves your memory for the visual aspects of a given experience ‚Äî though not for non-visual aspects, like a tour guide‚Äôs explanation. (In fact, taking photos decreases your memory for what you just heard!)‚Äù

‚ÄîGal Zauberman, Joseph F. Cullman, 3rd Professor of Marketing

ü§ù ‚ÄúWhile entrepreneurship refers to starting a new organization, and intrapreneurship refers to starting a new endeavor within an existing organization, *extrapreneurship* points to the importance of innovating across multiple organizations to create transformational and long-lasting change. If you are looking to create change in 2023, you don‚Äôt have to start something new. It‚Äôs more likely that you‚Äôll be able to make an even bigger difference if you connect with others across different organizations and sectors.‚Äù

‚ÄîTeresa Chahine, Sheila and Ron ‚Äô92 B.A. Marcelo Senior Lecturer in Social Entrepreneurship

üî¨‚ÄùWe should have confidence in our methods, confidence in our analysis, but humility in our interpretation. Too often, we find that ‚Äòfacts‚Äô were wrong: we foster an environment of unnecessary harm and risk when we move away from the probabilistic nature of science toward certainty, when the conclusions of analysis are far from certain.‚Äù

‚ÄîHoward Forman, Professor in the Practice of Management

Even in the middle of a New England winter, there‚Äôs a place on Yale‚Äôs campus that‚Äôs always warm, always in bloom, and always full of thriving vegetation.

The greenhouses of the Marsh Botanical Garden offer support for researchers, faculty and students at Yale, as well as an informative and eye-catching experience for visitors.

The Desert House display showcases plants that have evolved to adapt to very hot and arid environments. Unique water-storing capacities and heat- and sun-tolerance tactics are part of the wonder of these xerophytic plants.

Meanwhile, the Tropical Collection features various plants that are of cultural, botanical, and industrial interest in regions of the tropics. The collection includes representatives from all major groups of plants to reflect the incredible diversity of the tropical flora.

Learn more about the Marsh Botanical Garden, take a virtual tour of the grounds, and discover and some exciting plans for the future by visiting marshbotanicalgarden.yale.edu or by clicking the link in our bio. #Yale

captions:
VIDEO: When Yale School of Music student Ilana Zaks performs her Master of Musical Arts recital at Sprague Hall this week, it will not be a typical concert experience.

For starters, she‚Äôll begin the recital in the hall‚Äôs balcony with her audience seated on the main floor below her. During the whirlwind performance, she‚Äôll also wear LED lights while a video game is projected on a screen behind her, play alongside an actor silently performing scenes from Shakespeare‚Äôs ‚ÄúMuch Ado About Nothing,‚Äù and invite audience members to edge closer to the stage for a more intimate experience.

Above all, she‚Äôll tell a story, through the music itself and her own narration, about the history of classical music performance ‚Äî from the days when concerts were social occasions for the well-to-do in private residences to a period when they became more equitable entertainment in the public marketplace, and from a time when artists performed mostly in silent concert halls to the more experiential events of the modern era.

Zaks‚Äô recital takes place at 4:30 p.m. Dec. 10 in Sprague Memorial Hall, 470 College St. Admission is free.

Watch this video and then search "Zaks" at news.yale.edu to learn more about her upcoming performance.

VIDEO: For nearly 100 years, the Yale Peabody Museum‚Äôs dinosaurs have enthralled, inspired, and thrilled generations of visitors from New Haven and beyond. The beloved skeletons are currently in Canada being meticulously restored before they return to Yale‚Äôs campus.
 
‚ÄúThis is a treat for us dinosaur nerds,‚Äù said Peter May, of Research Casting International, the Trenton, Ontario, company tasked with cleaning, mending, and pose adjustments for the Peabody‚Äôs iconic dinosaur skeletons. ‚ÄúThese were the specimens that started paleontology.‚Äù
 
The showpiece skeletons will be remounted into poses that better reflect current scientific knowledge. ‚ÄúAll of the history behind it all, in my mind, it‚Äôs just amazing,‚Äù May said.

After a major renovation of the museum ‚Äì expected to be completed in 2024 ‚Äì the dinosaur skeletons will once again be on view in the Peabody‚Äôs public galleries.
 
Learn more about the #JourneyOfThePeabodyFossils and watch the full video at news.yale.edu/fossils. 
 
#Yale @yalepeabodymuseum
name: Yale

captions:
VIDEO: Precision and attention to detail are key components in the restoration process for several of the iconic dinosaur skeletons from Yale‚Äôs Peabody Museum of Natural History.

‚ÄúThe Peabody‚Äôs fossil mounts are treasures,‚Äù said Brian Ross of Research Casting International, the Canadian company tasked with cleaning, mending, and pose adjustments for the Peabody‚Äôs iconic dinosaur skeletons. ‚ÄúIt takes a lot of time and patience to make sure we produce the best possible mount.‚Äù

Changes to the 65-foot-long Brontosaurus will make the massive herbivore appear more lively and less plodding, which reflects current science. The tail, which previously dragged on the ground, will be longer and raised in the air. Its neck also will be lengthened.

After a major renovation of the museum expected to be completed in 2024, the dinosaurs will be back in New Haven for public view.

Learn more about the #JourneyOfThePeabodyFossils and watch the full video at news.yale.edu/fossils.

@yalepeabodymuseum #Yale

captions:
During a Veterans Day ceremony, Yale paid tribute to U.S. military veterans, including the generations of Yalies who have answered the call to service.

In times of war and times of peace, the desire to look beyond self interest in service of the common good has inspired countless service members as they sought to preserve the security and welfare of fellow citizens.

"I am deeply grateful for the veterans here with us today who have given of themselves to better the world ‚Äî and for the cadets and midshipmen of our ROTC programs who have similarly felt, and answered, the call to duty," said Yale President Peter Salovey, paying public tribute to the spirit of service and sacrifice.

Members of the Veterans Day Brass Ensemble, which included students from the Yale School of Music, played the National Anthem and taps, and performed a musical tribute to the men and women of each of the armed services.

Per tradition, veterans and current service members stood or stepped forward as the signature song of their branch of the military rang out.

Read more on how Yale is honoring military veterans and the spirit of service at news.yale.edu.

#Yale #VeteransDay2022
name: Yale

captions:
PODCAST: In this Veterans Day edition of Yale Talk, Meghan Brooks and Josh Lefkow of Yale Law School‚Äôs Veterans Legal Services Clinic join President Peter Salovey to discuss assisting veterans with legal needs related to their military service and return to civilian life.

Yale's rich tradition of service in the United States Armed Forces dates to the Revolutionary War and includes the nearly 30,000 Yalies who served in the first and second World Wars, Korea and Vietnam. 

As we reflect with gratitude on the heroism our veterans exemplify while serving, we also recognize with urgency the need to address the hardships that they face upon their return.

captions:
VIDEO: Today marks 225 years of the Grove Street Cemetery, the historic burial ground behind the brownstone wall and iron fence running along Grove and Prospect streets in New Haven.

On November 9, 1797, Martha Townsend became the first person buried here.

"We're glad to use this anniversary to uplift her and all the women buried in this sacred space," said Michael Morand ‚Äô87, ‚Äô93 MDiv, chair of the Friends of the Grove Street Cemetery organization.

"Knowing history helps us know ourselves," said Morand, who also serves as director of community engagement at Yale's Beinecke Library.

Since Townsend's interment, the cemetery has served as the resting place for many other important historical figures including Eli Whitney, Noah Webster, Walter Camp, Roger Sherman, Yale presidents, and hundreds of faculty members, alumni, and campus luminaries.

Learn more about the cemetery's history and the notable people buried here by visiting grovestreetcemetery.org.

@beineckelibrary #Yale #NewHaven #history

The Common Snapping Turtle, the largest freshwater turtle in Connecticut, can reach an impressive 18 inches long and 75 pounds. Hatchlings measure just 2.5 to 4 inches in length.

The ‚ÄòFor Humanity‚Äô campaign‚Äôs $1.2 billion commitment to student supports will help fund the promise of an affordable Yale education for generations to come. That makes it possible for students like Rudy Cordero ‚Äô24 to learn what they‚Äôll need to make an impact on the world:

While earning his associate‚Äôs degree from a community college in Chicago, Rudy worked full-time at a marketing firm and later at a technology start-up. Working alongside software engineers piqued his interest, and he began to wonder whether he might be able to pivot his career to similar work in one of the so-called STEM fields ‚Äî science, technology, engineering, and math. But going back to school felt like a pipe dream.

‚ÄúI knew that I wanted to pursue my education further, but I wasn‚Äôt sure I could afford it,‚Äù Rudy says. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm incredibly grateful for Yale‚Äôs commitment to financial advocacy and allowing me to attend an institution like this without having to think, how does my family continue to eat?‚Äù

Rudy enrolled in Yale‚Äôs Eli Whitney Students Program, which enables nontraditional students to earn Yale College degrees on a full or part-time basis.

‚ÄúYale‚Äôs nontraditional program is unlike almost any other one in the country,‚Äù Rudy says. ‚ÄúYale‚Äôs program specifically enabled me to decide on something that I understood was going to be challenging, that was going to allow me to take on this course load and remain flexible based on my current work schedule.‚Äù

He hopes to work in financial technology after he graduates, supporting nonprofit engagement in the e-commerce space. He also wants to give back to other students like him.

‚ÄúI want to help others with my background or who come from the same type of neighborhood that I did that didn‚Äôt have an amazing education system, but whose parents tried really hard to get them the skill sets that they needed to just get through high school and try to go to college,‚Äù Rudy says.

‚ÄúI talk to members of the community who are so excited to have someone from our neighborhood be here,‚Äù Rudy says. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a lot of pride that I bring back when I come home.‚Äù

Carla Staver‚Äôs research is going up in smoke ‚Äî and that's a good thing. The professor of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology has started hundreds of fires ‚Äî experimental ones ‚Äî in African savannas to learn more about how they start and stop burning, and their impact on the environment. Savanna fires are the most common fires on earth and make a large contribution to the global carbon cycle, so a quantitative understanding of their behavior is more critical than ever. 
 
Carla Staver is a member of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences (FAS), home to 1200+ faculty and 50 departments and programs that span the divisions of Humanities, Social Science, and Science, and the School of Engineering & Applied Science, and‚ÄØprovide the instruction to the students of‚ÄØYale College‚ÄØand the‚ÄØGraduate School of Arts and Sciences.

captions:
A Juneteenth 1925 celebration in Beaumont, Texas, captured by the Rev. Sir Solomon Jones.

This rare, early moving picture is among the @BeineckeLibrary‚Äôs collection of 29 films by Jones, digitized and available to the public online, which provide a rich record of African-American life in the 1920s.

#Juneteenth, which was declared a federal holiday in June 2021 and this year became an official Yale holiday, commemorates June 19, 1865 ‚Äî the day a U.S. Army general arrived in Galveston, Texas, to enforce the 2.5-year-old Emancipation Proclamation. Many Texans had defied it, continuing to hold enslaved people captive for years after they‚Äôd been legally freed.

Jones was born to emancipated parents in Tennessee in 1869 and moved to Oklahoma in 1889. There he became an influential minister, building and pastoring fifteen churches.

His films also include scenes from Jones‚Äô trips to 9 other states, New York City, and abroad ‚Äî France, England, Palestine, Switzerland, Italy, Germany, and parts of Northern Africa.

His subjects: church services, sports, Black colleges, Masonic meetings, families at home, a transcontinental footrace, Juneteenth celebrations, oil barons and other notables like self-made millionaire Madam C.J. Walker.

The ‚ÄòFor Humanity‚Äô campaign‚Äôs $1.2 billion commitment to student supports will help fund the promise of an affordable Yale education for generations to come. That makes it possible for students like Elisabeth Moore ‚Äô23 to learn what they‚Äôll need to make an impact on the world:

Elisabeth has always loved music. As a child, her home was filled with the sounds of old choir records that her mother would play. After taking lessons in piano and violin, she found her true passion in singing.

She joined her high school‚Äôs choir, and when an a cappella group from Yale came to visit and perform with the group, Elisabeth was awestruck. She recalls being impressed by the students‚Äô varied academic passions and musical talent.

‚ÄúI immediately felt like I could belong in a situation like this,‚Äù she says.

Elisabeth came to Yale expecting to major in music, but she ended up falling in love with Spanish literature and is pursuing a degree in Spanish and political science.

Still, she has found a way to fulfill her love of music through Yale extracurricular activities, like the Yale Glee Club and the Music in Schools Initiative, where she teaches voice lessons to New Haven Public School students.

‚ÄúI teach some amazing, amazing kids,‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúI have all my lessons on Thursday afternoons, which means I‚Äôm very tired at the end of the week. But somehow when I finish them, I feel so rejuvenated.‚Äù

Elisabeth incorporates her academic interests into the lessons she teaches, singing songs in Spanish with one student. Bringing together her love of music with her passion for Spanish is emblematic of what Elisabeth loves about Yale.

She also checks in with her students about more than just music, sharing about the day-to-day of her life as a Yale student and empathizing about the stresses of middle school.

‚ÄúI think back a lot to when I was in seventh grade and how chaotic it felt,‚Äù Elisabeth says. ‚ÄúFor me, what‚Äôs most important is treating them as I would have wanted myself to be treated when I was in seventh grade.‚Äù

The ‚ÄòFor Humanity‚Äô campaign‚Äôs $1.2 billion commitment to student supports will help fund the promise of an affordable Yale education for generations to come. That makes it possible for students like Jaida Morgan ‚Äô23 to learn what they‚Äôll need to make an impact on the world:

Jaida found her future career path when she was in fifth grade. ‚ÄúI became interested in cancer research when my best friend's mom, who was like a second mom to me, passed away from breast cancer very suddenly,‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúIt was my first experience with grieving the loss of someone close to me. I didn't want to have to see other people go through that.‚Äù

After high school, Jaida made her way to Yale. She was drawn to the research opportunities at the university, particularly the Science, Technology, and Research Scholars (STARS) program, which provides an avenue into those fields for women, first-generation, low-income students, and other underrepresented groups.

‚ÄúI decided to come to Yale because I knew, for one, that we have a really good cancer center here. I had also learned that through the STARS program, students could be paid for their research,‚Äù Jaida reflects.

Through STARS, Jaida has worked in two research labs and found a community of peers and mentors. Now a junior, she works as a research assistant to Gloria Huang, professor in the department of obstetrics, gynecology, and reproductive sciences, researching new therapeutic approaches to ovarian cancer.

Jaida is majoring in molecular, cellular, and developmental biology. She co-founded the Black Pre-Health Organization at Yale, which brings together students from the African diaspora to help each other prepare for careers in medicine, research, nursing, and public health. As she builds the foundations for a medical career, she also makes time to volunteer as a tutor for Bridges ESL, an organization that provides free English language lessons to people at Yale and in the New Haven community.

‚ÄúThere is no question that Yale changed my life,‚Äù Jaida says. ‚ÄúI wouldn't be able to attend Yale or pursue my research if it weren't for financial aid.‚Äù

title: Frederick Douglass: ‚ÄúWhat, to the American slave, is your Fourth of July?‚Äù
captions:
A reading of Frederick Douglass's 1852 Oration ‚Äî along with the Declaration of Independence ‚Äî is hosted each July 4 by the Beinecke Library.‚Å£
‚Å£
This year's reading is shared online by colleagues from Yale and New Haven. Find the full series here: https://beinecke.library.yale.edu/declarationDouglass2020‚Å£ ‚Å£(link in Highlights)
‚Å£
‚ÄúFor it is not light that is needed, but fire; it is not the gentle shower, but thunder. We need the storm, the whirlwind, and the earthquake. The feeling of the nation must be quickened; the conscience of the nation must be roused; the propriety of the nation must be startled; the hypocrisy of the nation must be exposed; and its crimes against God and man must be proclaimed and denounced.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWhat, to the American slave, is your 4th of July? I answer; a day that reveals to him, more than all other days in the year, the gross injustice and cruelty to which he is the constant victim.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£

title: Juneteenth 1925
captions:
In a rare, early moving picture, a Juneteenth 1925 celebration in Beaumont, Texas, is captured by the Rev. Sir Solomon Jones. It is among the @BeineckeLibrary‚Äôs collection of 29 films created by Jones, digitized and available to the public online, which provide a rich record of African-American life in the 1920s. ‚Å£
‚Å£
A Baptist minister and successful businessman, Jones took his role as traveling filmmaker seriously, writes film historian Martin Johnson. ‚ÄúJones‚Äôs films provide a sustained and intimate view of the people who built and sustained institutions of black life in Oklahoma.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
IndieWire called Jones‚Äô films ‚Äúthe most extensive film records we have of Southern and urban black life and culture at the time of rapid social and cultural change for African-Americans during the 1920s, the very beginning of the Great Migration.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Jones was born to emancipated parents in Tennessee in 1869 and moved to Oklahoma in 1889. There he became an influential minister, building and pastoring fifteen churches.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúJones was a fierce defender of black institutions, one of many African American leaders in Oklahoma who supported what came to be called ‚ÄúAll-Black towns,‚Äù writes Johnson. ‚ÄúJones filmed throughout the region, documenting communities and institutions that he was intimately familiar with, and, in many cases, helped develop.‚Äù ‚Å£
‚Å£
His films also include scenes from Jones‚Äô trips to 9 other states, New York City, and abroad ‚Äî France, England, Palestine, Switzerland, Italy, Germany, and parts of Northern Africa. ‚Å£
‚Å£
His subjects: church services, sports, Black colleges, Masonic meetings, families at home, a transcontinental footrace, Juneteenth celebrations, oil barons and other notables like self-made millionaire Madam C.J. Walker.‚Å£
‚Å£
#Juneteenth is the holiday commemorating the end of slavery in the U.S. The date references June 19, 1865 ‚Äî the day a U.S. Army general arrived in Galveston, Texas, to enforce the 2.5-year-old Emancipation Proclamation. Many Texans had defied it, continuing to hold enslaved people captive for years after they‚Äôd been legally freed. Juneteenth is now recognized as a state holiday or day of observance in 48 states.
‚Å£

captions:
Lulu Whidby, ‚ÄúHome Again Blues,‚Äù Black Swan Records 2005-B (1921)
.
Visit the Black Sound and the Archive Exhibition @YaleMusicLib to hear the full version of this recording. Free and open to the public through July 31, 2018.
.
We want to know more about Lulu Whidby, one of the early blues women who remains confounding obscure now. She most often turns up as an alluring footnote in histories of the music that focus on the pioneering recording era when Fletcher Henderson‚Äôs Novelty Orchestra laid down sides that shaped the sound of the Black Swan label. She may have been the Lulu Whidby who shows up in census records as having been born in Gwinnet, Georgia in 1871, the daughter of Joseph Allen Whidby and Sarah Orpy Cross. This Lulu Whidby passed away in 1949 in Wilcox, Georgia, long after the blues craze that supplied the soundtrack for the 1920s.
.
The Lulu Whidby of Black Swan covers an Irving Berlin song about longing and displacement (‚ÄúI‚Äôve been known to be a rolling stone for years‚Äù), reclaiming the migrancy and melancholia of blues feeling that Jewish composers and entertainers like Berlin, Gershwin, Jolson and others were actively coopting during this era of sonic and cinematic blackface. When Whidby sings with confident, full-throated conviction that she‚Äôs ‚Äúgoing home/knock at the door/home, just like before‚Ä¶‚Äù We might imagine this woman, possibly a southern migrant who made her way into the Black Swan studios, re-appropriating Berlin‚Äôs blues melodies with Georgia on her mind.
.
Black Swan Records. The first major record label to be owned, operated and marketed by African Americans, Black Swan was a recording industry endeavor directly designed to participate in the racial uplift movement of the 1920s. Founded in 1921 by Harry Pace, a former business partner of W.C. Handy‚Äôs, and with W.E.B. DuBois and other black arts luminaries named to its Board of Directors, the label made a conscious effort to counter racial stereotypes and broaden representations of African Americans in the public imaginary. Bandleader, composer, arranger, and pianist Fletcher Henderson served as the label‚Äôs recording director and leader of the house orchestra.
name: Yale

captions:
Ethel Waters, ‚ÄúJazzin‚Äô Babies Blues,‚Äù Black Swan Records 14117-A (1922?)
.
Visit the Black Sound and the Archive Exhibition @YaleMusicLib to hear the full version of this recording. Free and open to the public through July 31, 2018.
.
Black Swan‚Äôs biggest star, Pennsylvania-born Ethel Waters nearly saved the label from going under in its initial year of business. The vaudeville-bred Waters was a master of fluid, ‚Äúshape-shifting,‚Äù vocal interpretations and phrasings, the kinds of aesthetics that were largely at odds with those of southern-bred, rural blues singers.
.
On ‚ÄúJazzin‚Äô Babies Blues,‚Äù Waters tapped into the recorded blues craze that fellow vaudevillian Mamie Smith‚Äôs 1920 smash ‚ÄúCrazy Blues‚Äù had ignited. With a fluttery, high-pitched delivery, Waters sings a song here that captures the hysteria of pleasure triggered by this new, modern music made by ‚Äúthose jazzin‚Äô babies‚Ä¶ driving [her] insane.‚Äù All that vibrato in Waters‚Äô voice melds with her backing brass ensemble, reminding us of the instrumental virtuosity of the early, legendary blues and jazz women vocalists whose supple, robust voices evoked the drama, passion, and improvisational abandon of their fellow musicians.
.
As the late, great feminist blues archivist Rosetta Reitz puts it about Waters, she ‚Äúswung before the word was used to describe music.¬†¬†Her sweet bell-like clarity of tone and subtle use of nuance showed her innate taste and tireless invention.‚Äù
.
Black Swan Records. The first major record label to be owned, operated and marketed by African Americans, Black Swan was a recording industry endeavor directly designed to participate in the racial uplift movement of the 1920s. Founded in 1921 by Harry Pace, a former business partner of W.C. Handy‚Äôs, and with W.E.B. DuBois and other black arts luminaries named to its Board of Directors, the label made a conscious effort to counter racial stereotypes and broaden representations of African Americans in the public imaginary. Bandleader, composer, arranger, and pianist Fletcher Henderson served as the label‚Äôs recording director and leader of the house orchestra. The company folded in 1923.
name: Yale

captions:
Katie Crippen, ‚ÄúSing ‚ÄôEm for Mamma, Play ‚ÄôEm for Me,‚Äù Black Swan Records 2003-B (1921)
.
Visit the Black Sound and the Archive Exhibition @YaleMusicLib to hear the full version of this recording. Free and open to the public through July 31, 2018.
.
On the surface, Philadelphia-born Catherine ‚ÄúKatie‚Äù Crippen sounds like one of the many ‚Äúclassic female blues‚Äù singers who followed the path set by Mamie Smith, Alberta Hunter, and Ethel Waters, wildly inventive vaudevillians who bent the blues form to suit their highly dramatic interpretations of songs about love, sex, heartbreak, and the music itself.
.
Crippen, who performed as ‚ÄúLittle Katie Crippen‚Äù and ‚ÄúElla White‚Äù as well, makes use of gentle trills on ‚ÄúSing ‚ÄôEm for Mamma, Play ‚ÄôEm for Me‚Äù to convey the ways that she‚Äôs ‚Äúgoing crazy over that blue melody.‚Äù Blues convention, in other words, rules for the first minute and thirty-six seconds of this song until Crippen makes a surprising turn toward a spoken word (perhaps the first blues ‚Äúrap‚Äù on record?) recitation of the lyrics: ‚Äúplay ‚Äôem for Mama, sing ‚Äôem for me/sing ‚Äôem for me/I‚Äôm wild about the way you play that blue melody/go on, play it Daddy‚Ä¶ play it for your Mama ‚Äôtil the cows come home‚Ä¶ I know I shouldn‚Äôt holla but hey hey!‚Äù
.
Crippen made four sides for Black Swan Records and went on to perform with Fletcher Henderson‚Äôs Orchestra (under the Ella White pseudonym). She toured with revues featuring the likes of Fats Waller and a teen-age Count Basie.
.
Black Swan Records. The first major record label to be owned, operated and marketed by African Americans, Black Swan was a recording industry endeavor directly designed to participate in the racial uplift movement of the 1920s. Founded in 1921 by Harry Pace, a former business partner of W.C. Handy‚Äôs, and with W.E.B. DuBois and other black arts luminaries named to its Board of Directors, the label made a conscious effort to counter racial stereotypes and broaden representations of African Americans in the public imaginary. Bandleader, composer, arranger, and pianist Fletcher Henderson served as the label‚Äôs recording director and leader of the house orchestra. The company folded in 1923.

.
