There‚Äôs no room for shyness in the Black Box Theatre on the ground floor of Pless Hall, where Clinical Professor Nan Smithner teaches ‚ÄúPhysical Theatre & Improvisation,‚Äù a course that explores the art of improvisation through specific vocal and movement techniques.

Required for @nyusteinhardt‚Äôs Educational Theatre students, the course encourages undergraduate and graduate students to be playful and experimental as they discover ways to communicate with their entire body. In any given session, that means jumping, miming, groaning, or any combination of sounds and gestures that express an intention or idea.

‚ÄúI teach a lot through play, and improvisation is embedded in everything,‚Äù Smithner explains. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm advocating for the whole body to be expressive.‚Äù

We stopped by a recent session, where the students worked with Smithner and teaching Assistant Jordan Stewart on techniques used in Action Theatre. Read more about the cool course at the link in our bio.
name: New York University

captions:
@nyurubin Hall‚Äôs 13th floor is BACK‚Äîjust in time for Halloween.

Constructed in 1928, the building originally skipped 13 in the numbering of its floors, in keeping with an architectural tradition tied to folk beliefs about 13 as a bad luck number.

But after its recent passive house retrofit to make the residence hall climate-efficient and comfortable, Rubin reopened with an eye to the future and its 13th floor restored‚Äîand for good reason. A straightforward numbering system that matches the building‚Äôs architectural plans makes it easier for firefighters and other first responders to find their way to the right place in an emergency.

Plus, not everybody thinks 13 is spooky. According to @nyusteinhardt‚Äôs Jesse Bransford, an art professor and researcher on occult traditions, the number is actually considered good luck in some circles. No one knows for sure where triskaidekaphobia‚Äîor fear of 13‚Äîcomes from, but he has some theories about the cultural roots of the spooky association.

üìπ : Video by Jonathan King
name: New York University

As an intern at the American Song Archives in Tulsa this summer, Charlie Norbury (@nyutisch ‚Äô25) has been spending his days cataloging historic film reels for @woodyguthriecenter and @bobdylancenter, assessing the reels for damage, and making sure they're ready for digitization. 

While gaining relevant experience for his degree in moving image archiving and preservation, the grad student is also enjoying the opportunity to learn about Woody Guthrie's Oklahoma and NYC ties‚Äîand about Guthrie's profound influence on Bob Dylan.

The opportunity represents a full-circle moment for Charlie, who grew up in Oklahoma but left for NYC four years ago for undergrad at NYU. "New York can be overwhelming sometimes," he says. "It can be refreshing to come back to a place like this, where you feel a little bit more like you can slow down.‚Äù

@NYUTulsa's internship program offers students the chance to gain experience at a wide range of cultural institutions, government agencies, advocacy organizations, startups, and other businesses. Visit nyu.edu/tulsa to learn more.

captions:
Say hello to NYU‚Äôs newest global site: @NYUTulsa üí´

üìç A dynamic and diverse city with a rich and complex history, Tulsa offers many opportunities for NYU students and faculty as a destination for a study away semester, a summer internship, a short-term program, or research and creative work.

üíª At NYU Tulsa, NYUers can examine the United States‚Äô past, present, and future in a city emerging as a national leader in policy innovation, community-focused entrepreneurship, and tech-driven economic development.

üí° NYU students can explore Tulsa‚Äôs unique history while engaging with some of the most complex challenges the United States faces as a nation. It‚Äôs an ideal study away location for students who care about deep impact and the future of American cities.

üöÄ Every student at NYU Tulsa has the opportunity to do an internship, whether in the non-profit sector, government, or industry. NYU students can quickly plug into the network of people and organizations who are transforming the city.

‚ÄºÔ∏è Students who enroll full-time for the spring 2025 semester are eligible for the NYU Tulsa Scholarship, offering a minimum of $6,000 and a maximum of $12,000 in scholarship funds, even if they don‚Äôt currently receive financial aid.

For more information, visit nyu.edu/tulsa.

The year 2024 is an important one for democracy. Citizens in sixty-four countries‚Äîincluding of course in the United States‚Äîwill go to the polls to decide who should govern. To better understand where we are today, NYU is hosting a special course taught by Professor David Stasavage, the author of The Decline and Rise of Democracy: A Global History from Antiquity to Today. 

"Democracy: Past, Present and Future" is a one-credit course open to all undergraduate students this September and presumes neither previous experience in the study of politics nor an extensive knowledge of history. Read more about the course and how to register at the link in our bio. 

Our NYU Votes campaign is also in full swing with resources for students and information on participating in the election. Learn how to get involved at nyu.edu/nyu-votes

captions:
On October 13th, we had the privilege of hosting the ‚ÄúRevitalizing China Post-Pandemic‚Äù summit at NYU Shanghai!

Joined by professionals who are leaders in their respective fields, we welcomed over 120 students, including attendees from DKU and Shanghai Jiao Tong University. We‚Äôre grateful for your active participation and hope the event provided you with meaningful takeaways.

A heartfelt thank you to our distinguished speakers from McKinsey & Company, Savills, CBRE Group, Alibaba Group, YCP Solidiance, Wilton Partners, The Silk Initiative, Hotspex Company, and Tsinghua University. Their insights into China‚Äôs post-pandemic reforms, market trends, and their impact on industries such as real estate, finance, and international trade were invaluable and directly aligned with the focus of the summit.

As China navigates its post-pandemic recovery, the government‚Äôs bold reforms aim to stabilize growth, address structural weaknesses, and ensure long-term prosperity. This summit explored the impact of these reforms on sectors such as real estate, manufacturing, technology, and international trade.

Looking ahead, we‚Äôre excited to continue hosting events that bring important global discussions to our community. 

Stay tuned for more in the upcoming semester!

The microbiome in your gut is your best friend.
There are trillions of bacteria residing in our digestive system. Science has gradually revealed how the microbiome in our gut impacts our overall health, including mental health.

Dr. Aashish Jha, Assistant Professor in Biology from New York University Abu Dhabi, untangles some of the most common puzzles about our gut health.

Are probiotics good and can I consume them on a daily basis?

A fusion of art and sustainability, the remarkable winning installation for The Christo and Jeanne-Claude Award 2023 at Abu Dhabi Art is titled 'Shaheeq.'üé®

Inspired by the UAE's resilient mangrove trees and their role in combating climate change, this sculpture, created with ancient Rammed Earth techniques, embodies hope and environmental consciousness. üåø‚ú®

'Shaheeq' will  be a touring exhibition from NYU Abu Dhabi, Um El Emarat Park, and Jubail Mangrove Park, where it will eventually biodegrade back into the earth, returning to nature without a trace. A special thanks to the artists including Hala El Abora, Majd Alloush, and NYUAD Alum Vivi Zhu - for their visionary collaboration!

captions:
An interdisciplinary initiative at #NYUAbuDhabi spotlights how the Himalayan climate hotspot is jeopardizing the water supply for a quarter of humanity.

As the climate crisis worsens, the Himalayan water supply, which serves as a lifeline to several countries, including India, Pakistan, and China, among others, is under threat. 

Importantly, the scramble for uninterrupted access to ample fresh-water sources exacerbates geopolitical disputes within Asia and erodes interstate cooperation.

NYU Abu Dhabi‚Äôs Geopolitics and Ecology of Himalayan Water Project (GEHW) was founded to both study and raise awareness on this underreported crisis that threatens the stability and livelihood of 2.5 billion people.
#Livableplanet #COP28

From examining the Hajjar mountains' influence on local rainfall to investigating the resilience of Gulf coral reefs, NYU Abu Dhabi's Arab Center for Climate and Environmental Sciences (ACCESS) gathers vital climate data to expand knowledge on the unique regional environmental dynamics essential for confronting the climate crisis. üåç‚ú®

The mission of #NYUAD ACCESS is to confront the climate crisis by establishing comprehensive databases focused on the UAE and Arabian Gulf. üëè

‚ÄúAll of this knowledge really comes from large global models, but for this specific region, because of the vagaries of geography, the models cannot catch those fine details and cannot really give us answers. This is the gap in knowledge that we would like to fill,‚Äù said Associate Professor of Mathematics and Principle Investigator at ACCESS Francesco Paparella.

captions:
A childhood love for the sea and a seafarer‚Äôs dream led Noura Al Mansoori to know research on marine grass was her calling. üêö

Notoriously shy, dugongs are known to be one of the most difficult animals to spot in the ocean, let alone swim with. It happened for Al Mansoori years ago, on a trip with her family and friends in the Western Region of Abu Dhabi, when they spotted what has historically been noted in journals of famous expeditionaries as the inspiration behind mermaids: a herd of dugongs grazing off the coast.

The research assistant in NYU Abu Dhabi‚Äôs Marine Biology Lab is doing work that not many scientists are keen on conducting. Regularly she dives zapping seagrass 10 meters underwater as part of a series of experiments measuring the ecosystem‚Äôs health and what is becoming an increasingly diminished marine habitat for key species such as the gentle dugong. üí´
name: NYU Abu Dhabi

captions:
The speech made by @marietwestermann began with a quote from the Late Sheikh Khalifa. 

‚ÄúA University is not just a field of pure academic study; rather, it is a center of glorious intellectual, civilizational and cultural enlightenment.‚Äù

Westermann spoke of the impact the Class of 2022 had on the world, even when faced with the pandemic. 

"You learned that good change does not come easy, but you kept us focused on the enduring promise of NYU Abu Dhabi, which is also the promise of this country: that it is possible to make common cause for a better world. With your potential now unleashed, nothing is impossible. Our future is brighter with you at its leading edge. 

NYU Abu Dhabi graduates, you have been prepared for lives of purpose and care for others and for our shared planet. Please never stop shining your beautiful light."
name: NYU Abu Dhabi

captions:
As one of the most loved faculty on campus, @b_waterman's speech took students through a rollercoaster of emotions on their special day. 

"Working with many of you through the pandemic, I heard you express one anxiety over and over: Would we, your teachers, truly appreciate what you‚Äôve been through and respond with compassion?

I hope the answer has been yes. Personally, I learned something invaluable from my pandemic teaching. One of you ‚Äì I won‚Äôt name names ‚Äì wrote to me in advance of the fall 2020 semester to say that he was worried that taking a class about Contagion in the midst of Covid could be bad for his mental health. 

I resolved right then to make the course, and all of my teaching, from now until I someday inshallah retire, a resource for mental health rather than a hindrance. I hope the literature we read together, as difficult as it sometimes got, offered solace and survival skills."

#NYUAD2022 üíúüéì
name: NYU Abu Dhabi

captions:
Class of 2022's Yusril Nurhidayat gave a moving speech as the student speaker during commencement. 

In it, he detailed his inspiring journey that saw him go from struggling to afford to go to school in his hometown of Makassar in Indonesia to graduating from one of the world's best research universities. During this journey, his mother's support allowed him to persevere and reach unimaginable heights. 

#NYUAD2022 üíúüéì
name: NYU Abu Dhabi

captions:
Student Speaker Hessa AlAbbas made a powerful speech to her fellow classmates charging them with trying their very best at everything they do. 

"A dear friend of mine always says, life is a trial. Maybe we‚Äôll make the right decisions, maybe not, maybe there are no right decisions after all.

 So don‚Äôt worry too much, because the choices we make honor where we are in life, what we‚Äôre going through and what has brought us to those very moments. So if all we can do is try, then let‚Äôs try our hardest, to grow and to learn. We don‚Äôt need there to be any right decisions, we need intention and ambition, to do and to be, and I can vouch that the class of 2022 definitely knows ambition."

#NYUAD2022 üíúüéì
